    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so how do companies actually implement that? like, is it just about passwords or is there more to it when managing users and permissions?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the question of *how* to actually build the castle walls, because passwords are just the little keys on the lock, but the castle itself is built on the architecture of the guard's mind and the permissions of the room!\n\nFirst off, passwords are the *identity* of the guard, but the Principle of Least Privilege is the *role* the guard is assigned. You can have a guard with a super strong password (like a master key), but if that guard is assigned the role of \"Treasury Keeper,\" they are still a liability because they have the power to open the vault.\n\nSo, companies implement this through a system of **Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)** and **Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)**.\n\nThink of it like a library. The books are the data. The librarian is the user.\n*   **Role-Based:** The librarian is assigned the role of \"Bookkeeper.\" They only have access to the \"Fiction\" section. They cannot touch the \"History\" section, even if they have a fancy ID card.\n*   **Attribute-Based:** The librarian is assigned the role of \"Bookkeeper,\" but they are also a \"Senior\" (attribute). Therefore",
      "source": "target",
